<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<knowl mode="exercise" xmlns="https://spatext.clontz.org" version="0.2">
    <intro>
        <p>
            Let <m>{\bf v} = \bigl\langle {{v_1}},{{v_2}},{{v_3}} \bigr\rangle</m> and <m>{\bf w} = \bigl\langle {{w_1}}, {{w_2}}, {{w_3}} \bigr\rangle.</m>
        </p>
    </intro>    
            
                <knowl>
                    <content>
                        <p>
                            Compute the {{op_text}} product <m>\mathbf{v} {{op}} \mathbf{w}</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </content>
                    <outtro>
                        <p>
                            <m>\mathbf{v} {{op}} \mathbf{w} = {{u}}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </outtro>
                </knowl>
                <knowl>
                    <content>
                        <p>
                            Is the vector projection <m>\mathbf{w}_\| = {\rm proj}_\mathbf{v} \mathbf{w}</m> parallel to <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, anti-parallel to <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, or is it the zero vector? Justify your answer.
                        </p>
                    </content>
                    <outtro>
                        <p>
                            The vector <m>\mathbf{w}_\|</m> is {{orient}} to <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, since <m>\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{w} = {{vdotw}}</m> is {{vdotw_sign}}. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            In particular, <m>\mathbf{w}_\| = \left\langle {{wp_1}}, {{wp_2}}, {{wp_3}} \right\rangle,</m> though computing this is not necessary for the above answer.
                        </p>
                    </outtro>
                </knowl>
                <knowl>
                    <content>
                        <p>
                            If <m>\mathbf{x}</m> is a vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> that has magnitude <m>{{mx}}</m> and makes an angle of <m>{{theta}}</m> {{unit}} with <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, find the {{op_text_2}} product <m>{{op2}}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </content>
                    <outtro>
                        <p>
                            <m>{{op2}} = \|\mathbf{v}\| \|\mathbf{x}\| {{op_trig}}({{theta}}) = {{prod2}}.</m>
                        </p>
                    </outtro>
                </knowl>
